  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). The pump operates in continuous in vivo deployment for the duration of cardiopulmonary bypass surgery, which may extend to 6 hours or more under demanding perfusion conditions. Roller-head and centrifugal pump assemblies used in clinical settings are subject to bearing wear, seal degradation, and motor driver fluctuations that can alter impeller rotational fidelity during extended duty cycles. All CFD simulations and validation experiments were conducted under nominal hardware conditions with factory-calibrated pump assemblies exhibiting no measurable mechanical degradation.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cou1-hemolysis-rh-criterion",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-cfd-hemolysis-worst-case",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-centrifugal-bp-rans-hemolysis",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-experimental-piv-2023",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-hemolysis-bench-2023"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. The device operates in vivo in a continuous duty cycle that may span 6 hours or more at elevated flow rates, during which the physical pump hardware is exposed to thermal loading, bearing wear, and potential seal micro-leakage that can perturb impeller speed and flow geometry. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
